1
00:00:11,400 --> 00:00:15,200
<i>Good morning. It's 6 a.m.</i>
<i>on a beautiful morning in Boston.</i>

2
00:00:15,400 --> 00:00:16,600
<i>These are the top stories:</i>

3
00:00:16,800 --> 00:00:20,900
<i>Mayor White's assistant has met</i>
<i>with the Redevelopment Authority...</i>

4
00:00:21,100 --> 00:00:24,100
<i>...over the controversy</i>
<i>on the Town Heights project.</i>

5
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:28,000
<i>Saugus: Police have arrested</i>
<i>contractor James McManus...</i>

6
00:00:28,200 --> 00:00:30,800
<i>...on $ 23 million grant</i>
<i>and bribery charges...</i>

7
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:35,400
<i>...in connection with the Mystic</i>
<i>River extension. Hyannis Port....</i>

8
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:43,074
Delicious Vegan Sausages, Cheese
and Burgers - Vegusto.co.uk

9
00:00:47,300 --> 00:00:50,200
Mrs. Levine is day five
post-cholecystectomy.

10
00:00:50,400 --> 00:00:54,300
She remains afebrile and her previous
anorexia is gone, draining well.

11
00:00:54,500 --> 00:00:57,900
An AP chest film is clear.
Her white count is nine-four.

12
00:00:58,100 --> 00:01:01,500
BUN has stabilized at 40.2,
good output of 1 600cc's.

13
00:01:01,700 --> 00:01:03,600
-Blood cultures?
-No growth times two.

14
00:01:04,100 --> 00:01:07,300
Well, Harris can't nail us on this one.

15
00:01:07,500 --> 00:01:08,600
Next case.

16
00:01:12,600 --> 00:01:15,400
-lt was a long time ago.
-And is he good?

17
00:01:15,600 --> 00:01:17,900
Yeah, he can really break it up!

18
00:01:18,100 --> 00:01:19,600
Billy's weird.

19
00:01:19,800 --> 00:01:21,400
He gets so tired.

20
00:01:21,600 --> 00:01:23,100
Do you like this lipstick?

21
00:01:23,400 --> 00:01:24,600
She was terrific.

22
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:26,600
lt's 32 now and going fast.

23
00:01:26,800 --> 00:01:28,300
He can't afford to get out.

24
00:01:28,500 --> 00:01:30,800
l got a thousand shares of that.

25
00:01:31,800 --> 00:01:36,200
We have to have the AP, lateral and
1 0 units done before they can begin.

26
00:01:36,400 --> 00:01:39,100
lt says here, type and cross-match
was done yesterday.

27
00:01:39,300 --> 00:01:41,700
Just standard workup procedure.

28
00:01:42,200 --> 00:01:43,000
Well, l don't know.

29
00:01:43,200 --> 00:01:45,700
So it was a clear case of endocarditis.

30
00:01:45,900 --> 00:01:48,200
We're ready when you are,
Dr. Wheeler.

31
00:01:48,400 --> 00:01:49,700
No response to antibiotics.

32
00:01:54,100 --> 00:01:55,200
Cut her, okay?

33
00:01:55,400 --> 00:01:57,800
-Sponge.
-Begin to tie off.

34
00:02:03,900 --> 00:02:06,000
<i>It's all politics.</i>
<i>Today, for instance...</i>

35
00:02:06,200 --> 00:02:11,000
...Rudnick says to me, ''l hear you're
the new chief resident in surgery.''

36
00:02:11,200 --> 00:02:13,800
-That's great!
-He was testing me.

37
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,100
Then he says that Harris told him...

38
00:02:16,300 --> 00:02:19,600
...that Mark Bellows was going to be
the next chief resident.

39
00:02:19,800 --> 00:02:22,000
-Wonderful, Mark.
-But here's the thing.

40
00:02:22,200 --> 00:02:26,200
He waited for me to say l knew
about it. That wouldn't look right.

41
00:02:26,400 --> 00:02:30,400
That would look as if l expected it.
So l said l hadn't heard anything.

42
00:02:30,600 --> 00:02:32,900
You've wanted it for two years.

43
00:02:33,100 --> 00:02:36,000
But there's no point
in saying that, is there?

44
00:02:36,200 --> 00:02:37,400
l said...

45
00:02:37,700 --> 00:02:40,400
...l thought it'd be wonderful
if it happened.

46
00:02:40,600 --> 00:02:43,700
l said Chandler was doing
an excellent job as chief resident.

47
00:02:43,900 --> 00:02:47,200
But l said there was a little room
left for improvement.

48
00:02:47,400 --> 00:02:49,200
Chandler's damn good.

49
00:02:50,400 --> 00:02:52,600
l really laid it on thick
with old Rudnick.

50
00:02:52,800 --> 00:02:57,400
l told him l was following his hepatic
research, cited some references.

51
00:02:57,600 --> 00:02:59,200
He was impressed.

52
00:02:59,400 --> 00:03:01,600
Procedure went well too.

53
00:03:01,800 --> 00:03:04,300
So all in all, it was a good day.

54
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:08,600
l'm gonna take a shower.
Can you grab me a beer before dinner?

55
00:03:08,800 --> 00:03:10,100
Hey, Mark.

56
00:03:10,300 --> 00:03:11,400
Get your own beer.

57
00:03:11,800 --> 00:03:14,900
-Honey, for chrissakes, come on.
-l want to take a shower.

58
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:17,400
-l was on call last night.
-So was l.

59
00:03:17,600 --> 00:03:19,300
l know, but l had two arrests...

60
00:03:19,500 --> 00:03:22,600
...aortic aneurysm blew at 4 a.m.,
had to be done stat.

61
00:03:22,800 --> 00:03:26,500
So l didn't get any sleep, and
l'd really like to take a shower.

62
00:03:28,800 --> 00:03:30,800
lf you don't mind.

63
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:32,700
l had a hard day too.

64
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:36,800
You get in the shower faster
than any person alive.

65
00:03:37,300 --> 00:03:39,300
Have a beer.
You'll feel better.

66
00:03:42,500 --> 00:03:44,900
l know what'd make me feel better.

67
00:03:45,100 --> 00:03:47,100
Goddamn doctors.

68
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:50,500
Couldn't have fallen
in love with a nurse.

69
00:03:53,400 --> 00:03:55,600
Dorothy on the eighth floor.

70
00:03:56,500 --> 00:03:58,200
She liked me.

71
00:04:00,500 --> 00:04:02,500
My own apartment.

72
00:04:05,900 --> 00:04:07,400
Did you hear about Louis?

73
00:04:07,600 --> 00:04:08,800
What about Louis?

74
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,700
They passed him up
as assistant professor.

75
00:04:11,900 --> 00:04:15,200
Guy's really paid his dues too.
Now they don't take him.

76
00:04:15,400 --> 00:04:18,500
Plus his son is waiting
for a kidney transplant.

77
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:20,500
Did you start dinner?

78
00:04:22,100 --> 00:04:23,100
What?

79
00:04:23,400 --> 00:04:24,500
Did you start dinner?

80
00:04:24,700 --> 00:04:29,400
-Did you hear anything l said?
-lt's in the fridge. Just heat it up.

81
00:04:29,600 --> 00:04:33,800
-l was telling you about my day.
-l had a hard day too.

82
00:04:34,500 --> 00:04:36,500
Just go heat it up.

83
00:04:36,700 --> 00:04:40,500
Why is it, whenever we're about
to fight, you're always undressed?

84
00:04:40,700 --> 00:04:43,500
What's the big deal?
Just heat up the stew.

85
00:04:43,700 --> 00:04:46,500
-Why won't you help out?
-ls that the way you see it?

86
00:04:46,700 --> 00:04:49,400
l make my concessions.
You always take a shower first.

87
00:04:49,600 --> 00:04:50,500
l don't.

88
00:04:50,700 --> 00:04:53,200
You do too,
and l'm getting tired of it.

89
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:56,000
Honey, come on.

90
00:04:56,200 --> 00:04:57,000
Don't call me honey.

91
00:04:57,200 --> 00:05:00,800
l'm trying to tell you about my day.
Something that happened.

92
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:03,500
Your days are always the same.

93
00:05:05,500 --> 00:05:07,200
What is that supposed to mean?

94
00:05:07,400 --> 00:05:09,300
Just politics, that's all.

95
00:05:09,500 --> 00:05:12,500
Who said what to whom.
Who's rising, who's falling.

96
00:05:12,700 --> 00:05:15,300
Who's made a good move, a bad move.
Politics!

97
00:05:15,500 --> 00:05:18,400
Somebody has to be interested
in hospital politics.

98
00:05:18,600 --> 00:05:19,700
You certainly are not.

99
00:05:19,900 --> 00:05:23,100
l thought you were a surgical
resident, not a political one.

100
00:05:23,600 --> 00:05:25,300
l like politics.

101
00:05:25,500 --> 00:05:28,700
They interest me. Just because
you're always looking for--

102
00:05:29,300 --> 00:05:31,400
You want me to heat up
the dinner, is that it?

103
00:05:32,500 --> 00:05:34,700
l want some respect.

104
00:05:34,900 --> 00:05:37,300
Susan, come on.
Don't leave again.

105
00:05:37,800 --> 00:05:39,900
Why can't you share
half the responsibility?

106
00:05:40,100 --> 00:05:42,300
l share more than
half the responsibility!

107
00:05:42,500 --> 00:05:44,700
-No need to shout.
-Why are you running off?

108
00:05:44,900 --> 00:05:47,800
You think l want this?
Let me tell you something.

109
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:50,500
l make concessions
for this so-called relationship.

110
00:05:50,700 --> 00:05:53,500
l know it's hard on you politically.

111
00:06:00,600 --> 00:06:01,600
Susan, don't go.

112
00:06:03,900 --> 00:06:06,100
You know what the trouble with you is?

113
00:06:06,300 --> 00:06:08,700
All you care about
is being chief resident.

114
00:06:08,900 --> 00:06:12,400
You know what your trouble is?
You don't want a relationship.

115
00:06:12,600 --> 00:06:14,900
Look at you.
You run away from it.

116
00:06:15,100 --> 00:06:16,700
This is ridiculous.

117
00:06:17,500 --> 00:06:19,000
You don't want a lover...

118
00:06:19,200 --> 00:06:21,200
...you want a goddamn wife!

119
00:07:02,800 --> 00:07:04,300
Bastard.

120
00:07:16,300 --> 00:07:18,100
l have a bleeder here.

121
00:07:18,300 --> 00:07:20,800
-l need more suction.
-Clamp.

122
00:07:24,400 --> 00:07:27,800
He's not di-toxic.
He has advanced ASHD.

123
00:07:30,300 --> 00:07:32,400
l just bought some at 43.

124
00:07:32,600 --> 00:07:36,100
Yeah, l hear they have management
problems. l sold at 37.

125
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:42,500
How are you?

126
00:07:42,800 --> 00:07:44,800
l'm fine. The case went well.
No problem.

127
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:46,300
Good.

128
00:07:47,700 --> 00:07:50,500
l'm really sorry about last night.

129
00:07:50,700 --> 00:07:52,300
So am l.

130
00:07:52,500 --> 00:07:55,200
-You want to have some lunch?
-l have class.

131
00:07:55,400 --> 00:07:58,200
You don't think this is
more important than the class?

132
00:07:58,400 --> 00:08:02,200
That class is the only time
l get out of this damn hospital.

133
00:08:02,400 --> 00:08:05,100
Can you understand that?
lt's important to me!

134
00:08:05,800 --> 00:08:07,200
You're impossible!

135
00:08:07,400 --> 00:08:09,600
Seven, eight, step!

136
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:14,000
Back. Step.

137
00:08:15,100 --> 00:08:16,300
Out!

138
00:08:18,400 --> 00:08:21,800
One, two, down three,
up four and open.

139
00:08:22,600 --> 00:08:25,200
And one and two,
three and four.

140
00:08:25,500 --> 00:08:26,900
Stretch.

141
00:08:27,700 --> 00:08:29,500
Walk two, three, four...

142
00:08:29,700 --> 00:08:33,200
...and five and six, seven,
eight and back.

143
00:08:33,400 --> 00:08:36,300
-You gonna leave Mark?
-l don't know.

144
00:08:36,500 --> 00:08:37,700
l went home last night.

145
00:08:38,400 --> 00:08:39,400
Again?

146
00:08:40,800 --> 00:08:42,500
He's impossible.

147
00:08:43,300 --> 00:08:45,400
Did you see Dr. Richards?

148
00:08:47,400 --> 00:08:48,300
l don't know.

149
00:08:48,500 --> 00:08:52,800
Apparently you can tell by looking at
the cervix. lt's a different color.

150
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:56,900
He did the lab tests and he says
l'm definitely 8 to 1 0 weeks pregnant.

151
00:08:57,100 --> 00:09:00,500
So Dr. Richards is doing
a D and C tomorrow.

152
00:09:01,300 --> 00:09:03,500
For menstrual irregularity.

153
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:06,600
lt's simple, isn't it?

154
00:09:07,300 --> 00:09:08,800
Are you worried?

155
00:09:09,300 --> 00:09:13,100
l know you do this every day but, sure,
l'm worried. Who wouldn't be?

156
00:09:13,700 --> 00:09:16,800
lt'll be fine, Nancy.
lt's routine procedure.

157
00:09:23,800 --> 00:09:25,600
We're going to the lce Capades.

158
00:09:26,400 --> 00:09:27,400
lt's real crowded.

159
00:09:27,600 --> 00:09:28,600
Patient on call?

160
00:09:28,800 --> 00:09:32,400
-Coming right down, Dr. Cowans.
-The instruments are autoclaved.

161
00:09:32,600 --> 00:09:35,300
Let's teach you fellas
some anesthesiology.

162
00:09:35,500 --> 00:09:37,100
This is your standard anesthesia.

163
00:09:37,300 --> 00:09:41,800
You've got two main wall lines.
Nitrous oxide on the left and oxygen.

164
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:44,300
We got a case today that's a D and C.

165
00:09:44,500 --> 00:09:47,800
lt's one of Dr. Richard's cases.
Actually, it's a TAB.

166
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:52,500
That's a therapeutic abortion.
Keep it clean. lt's a married patient.

167
00:09:53,200 --> 00:09:55,600
On the cart here,
we got two manometers...

168
00:09:55,800 --> 00:09:59,000
...with flow valves here and here
to regulate gas.

169
00:09:59,200 --> 00:10:01,500
We got emergency oxygen down here...

170
00:10:01,700 --> 00:10:04,300
...which we checked and that's full.

171
00:10:04,500 --> 00:10:08,000
During surgery, we'll be recording this
and the vital signs.

172
00:10:08,200 --> 00:10:09,400
Hey, how is Bess?

173
00:10:09,600 --> 00:10:10,800
l don't know.

174
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:12,400
ln and out.

175
00:10:14,400 --> 00:10:17,400
Boy, she has more rails
than anybody l know.

176
00:10:17,600 --> 00:10:18,900
She's seeing a shrink now.

177
00:10:19,100 --> 00:10:20,800
One, two, three, up!

178
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:22,800
Anybody we know?

179
00:10:23,400 --> 00:10:26,900
Morning, Nancy. Remember me?
l'm Dr. Cowans.

180
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:31,900
That's right, dear,
and you'll have a nice long sleep.

181
00:10:32,200 --> 00:10:35,400
Pre-op, she's received a 0.0 1
of Demerol and 0.4 of atropine...

182
00:10:35,600 --> 00:10:37,900
...so believe me,
she's pretty relaxed.

183
00:10:38,100 --> 00:10:42,700
l'll say she's relaxed!
Come on, Mrs. Greenly, on your back.

184
00:10:42,900 --> 00:10:44,200
That's it.

185
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:47,000
-Gonna meet me for lunch?
-l don't know.

186
00:10:47,200 --> 00:10:48,900
l'll let you know, okay?

187
00:10:50,200 --> 00:10:51,700
l'll be in the lounge.

188
00:10:51,900 --> 00:10:55,100
Henry might be calling,
and if he does, you know....

189
00:10:55,300 --> 00:10:58,200
-Okay, no problem.
-Yeah, okay.

190
00:10:59,500 --> 00:11:02,000
-Good afternoon, Tom.
-Afternoon, Jim. How's our lady?

191
00:11:02,300 --> 00:11:03,100
Just about ready.

192
00:11:03,300 --> 00:11:04,800
l'm still awake.

193
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:07,300
-But not for long, dear.
-You promise?

194
00:11:07,500 --> 00:11:10,600
l'll induce with sodium Pentothal,
give an lV by syringe.

195
00:11:10,800 --> 00:11:12,400
Nance, what l want you to do...

196
00:11:12,600 --> 00:11:16,300
...is start counting from 1 00
backwards real slow, okay?

197
00:11:16,800 --> 00:11:18,400
Here we go.

198
00:11:18,600 --> 00:11:21,700
-A hundred.
-Ninety-nine...

199
00:11:22,400 --> 00:11:24,200
...ninety-eight...

200
00:11:25,200 --> 00:11:27,000
...ninety-seven...

201
00:11:27,900 --> 00:11:29,600
...ninety-six....

202
00:11:31,700 --> 00:11:33,800
lt's quick. Stop the pentothal.

203
00:11:34,100 --> 00:11:36,400
You see, pentothal isn't
really an anesthetic.

204
00:11:36,600 --> 00:11:39,300
Any deep pain right now
and she'd wake right up.

205
00:11:39,500 --> 00:11:42,300
What we need for anesthesia is gas.

206
00:11:42,500 --> 00:11:44,900
First l'll inject some succinylcholine.

207
00:11:45,100 --> 00:11:49,100
l want you to watch her chest gauge
because she'll stop breathing.

208
00:11:52,700 --> 00:11:56,300
She's now experiencing
complete muscular paralysis.

209
00:11:56,500 --> 00:11:59,600
She's got three minutes
to breathe or she'll suffocate.

210
00:11:59,800 --> 00:12:01,600
So now we intubate.

211
00:12:02,200 --> 00:12:04,400
Taking a laryngoscope like so.

212
00:12:04,700 --> 00:12:06,600
Hold her head
in an extended position.

213
00:12:06,800 --> 00:12:10,300
Enter laterally, put up
the base of the tongue, up and out...

214
00:12:10,500 --> 00:12:12,100
...visualizing the trachea.

215
00:12:12,300 --> 00:12:14,700
There it is, fellas. Take a look.

216
00:12:15,300 --> 00:12:17,200
You see it?
lt's right over there.

217
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:20,600
Come on, guys!

218
00:12:20,800 --> 00:12:24,200
Take our tube and enter here.

219
00:12:25,800 --> 00:12:29,000
ln the middle of surgery,
l'll switch over to the telothane.

220
00:12:30,700 --> 00:12:32,100
Stirrups up?

221
00:12:34,600 --> 00:12:36,100
How is John?

222
00:12:36,300 --> 00:12:39,900
His fever broke today.
He'll go back to school tomorrow.

223
00:12:40,100 --> 00:12:42,000
Now we can check
the pupillary reflexes.

224
00:12:42,200 --> 00:12:45,700
Though she's unconscious,
the pupils should react to light...

225
00:12:45,900 --> 00:12:48,300
...and let us know
that the old brain is okay.

226
00:12:48,500 --> 00:12:53,300
That's it. Anesthesia's the easiest job
in the world until something goes wrong.

227
00:12:53,500 --> 00:12:56,900
lt's 99% boredom
and 1 % scared-shitless panic...

228
00:12:57,200 --> 00:13:01,300
...which we try to avoid.
The patient's yours, Dr. Richards.

229
00:13:01,500 --> 00:13:03,200
lf you move in behind me...

230
00:13:03,400 --> 00:13:06,600
...you'll see what l am going to do
for this young woman.

231
00:13:06,800 --> 00:13:07,800
Some music, please.

232
00:13:10,500 --> 00:13:14,400
Actually, what l'm going to do
is get her out of a hell of a mess.

233
00:13:15,100 --> 00:13:16,400
She's pregnant.

234
00:13:16,600 --> 00:13:19,000
She doesn't want her husband to know.

235
00:13:20,200 --> 00:13:22,300
lt's none of my business.

236
00:13:22,800 --> 00:13:25,700
l'm just her surgeon.
l don't run her life.

237
00:13:27,900 --> 00:13:30,500
So in fact, our task is simplified...

238
00:13:30,700 --> 00:13:33,400
...when the uterus is
anteverted and anteflexed.

239
00:13:33,600 --> 00:13:37,500
This is a function of the muscular
attachments, of which there are five.

240
00:13:37,700 --> 00:13:38,800
You should know them.

241
00:13:39,700 --> 00:13:43,500
They're the broad ligaments,
the round and cardinal ligaments...

242
00:13:43,700 --> 00:13:47,100
...and the endopelvic fascia,
the uterosacral ligaments.

243
00:13:52,700 --> 00:13:53,700
Something wrong?

244
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:58,000
She just threw a PVC,
and her blood pressure's falling.

245
00:13:58,700 --> 00:14:00,400
l got 90 over 60.

246
00:14:00,600 --> 00:14:03,700
She's fully oxygenated.
Red as a cherry down here.

247
00:14:03,900 --> 00:14:06,100
How much longer you got?

248
00:14:07,500 --> 00:14:08,900
Just a couple of minutes.

249
00:14:09,100 --> 00:14:11,600
l don't like this.
Her blood pressure is still falling.

250
00:14:13,900 --> 00:14:14,800
Damn!

251
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:18,700
We should stop. She may be getting
too much vagal stimulation.

252
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:20,300
Jesus Christ.

253
00:14:20,600 --> 00:14:21,400
What's the matter?

254
00:14:21,600 --> 00:14:23,900
l don't know.
Nothing's the matter!

255
00:14:24,100 --> 00:14:26,300
Something's the matter.
She's going to arrest!

256
00:14:26,500 --> 00:14:27,400
l can't find anything!

257
00:14:44,500 --> 00:14:47,300
l get a 1 00 over 80.
Her pressure's climbing.

258
00:14:47,500 --> 00:14:51,200
Let's finish up. l'd like to get
this mother off the table.

259
00:14:53,700 --> 00:14:55,500
Sponge, please.

260
00:14:58,500 --> 00:15:02,000
One-twenty over 80 and climbing.
She's okay.

261
00:15:03,800 --> 00:15:07,500
-These tissues can go to pathology.
-Can l start bringing her out?

262
00:15:07,700 --> 00:15:09,200
Yeah, bring her out, Jim.

263
00:15:14,200 --> 00:15:17,300
Okay, Mrs. Greenly,
it's time to wake up.

264
00:15:17,600 --> 00:15:19,000
Okay, Nancy?

265
00:15:19,200 --> 00:15:21,900
Mrs. Greenly? Wake up.

266
00:15:22,300 --> 00:15:25,100
Nance, can you give me
a cough, please?

267
00:15:39,700 --> 00:15:44,000
Jesus Christ!
Her pupils are fixed and dilated.

268
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:47,500
The pupils, they're fixed.

269
00:15:48,100 --> 00:15:49,600
Dilated.

270
00:15:53,700 --> 00:15:55,800
Oh, my God!

271
00:15:56,700 --> 00:16:00,200
Pre-op diagnosis,
acute gastric ulceration.

272
00:16:00,400 --> 00:16:02,800
Post-op diagnosis, the same.

273
00:16:03,300 --> 00:16:05,900
Surgeon, Dr. Wilson.

274
00:16:08,300 --> 00:16:11,300
-Where's Schwartz? Cholecystectomy?
-Bed three.

275
00:16:13,900 --> 00:16:17,800
-Mr. Schwartz, l'm Dr. Bellows.
-You don't got to talk so loud.

276
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:19,200
How you feel?

277
00:16:19,400 --> 00:16:20,500
Just ''eh''?

278
00:16:20,700 --> 00:16:23,300
You want to get on your side
for me, please?

279
00:16:23,500 --> 00:16:26,200
-On your side.
-Speak up, l can't hear you.

280
00:16:26,400 --> 00:16:29,000
What'd they give you
in that operating room?

281
00:16:29,200 --> 00:16:30,500
Do you have any pain?

282
00:16:30,700 --> 00:16:34,000
lf l had any pain,
l would go see a doctor.

283
00:16:34,400 --> 00:16:37,000
Now you want to breathe
for me real easy?

284
00:16:38,600 --> 00:16:40,600
That's it. Slowly.

285
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:44,200
She was given narceine
to rule out pre-op narcotic....

286
00:16:45,600 --> 00:16:46,500
Easy!

287
00:16:46,700 --> 00:16:49,600
Two units without effect,
a few peripheral fasciculations.

288
00:16:49,800 --> 00:16:51,500
So it's not succinylcholine?

289
00:16:53,400 --> 00:16:55,900
Delayed return of consciousness
of cryptogenic origin.

290
00:16:58,600 --> 00:17:02,000
l see no reason not to transfer her
to the intensive care unit.

291
00:17:02,200 --> 00:17:04,500
Mr. Schwartz, you're going to be fine.

292
00:17:04,700 --> 00:17:06,400
That's what you think!

293
00:17:09,300 --> 00:17:13,200
-A grim prognosis, to say the least.
-Rather tragic.

294
00:17:13,500 --> 00:17:15,300
Someone should notify Dr. George.

295
00:17:15,500 --> 00:17:17,800
He'll want to review
the anesthetic protocol.

296
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:20,000
Right, he's been paged.

297
00:17:20,200 --> 00:17:22,300
Looks like
another anesthetic reaction.

298
00:17:24,400 --> 00:17:27,400
Page Dr. Bendix.
4-4-4-3-2.

299
00:17:27,600 --> 00:17:28,500
Check.

300
00:17:28,700 --> 00:17:30,600
George is not here.

301
00:17:30,800 --> 00:17:33,900
No, Dr. Bendix. Bendix!

302
00:17:34,100 --> 00:17:36,800
Maybe he left the hospital.
Try his office.

303
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:40,400
Could you page Dr. Wheeler, please?

304
00:17:40,600 --> 00:17:43,900
So you see, Jimmy,
your kidneys are sick.

305
00:17:44,100 --> 00:17:45,300
They don't work right.

306
00:17:45,500 --> 00:17:49,000
We need to take out the sick kidneys
and put in a new one.

307
00:17:49,200 --> 00:17:50,100
Today?

308
00:17:50,500 --> 00:17:53,200
No, not today.
We have to wait until...

309
00:17:53,400 --> 00:17:55,500
...there's a kidney we can put in.

310
00:17:55,700 --> 00:17:56,600
Tomorrow?

311
00:17:57,100 --> 00:18:00,100
l don't know when.
But it could be a while.

312
00:18:01,700 --> 00:18:05,000
<i>Dr. Wheeler, call extension 3-5-6.</i>

313
00:18:05,200 --> 00:18:08,200
You can have one of these.
Which color do you like?

314
00:18:10,300 --> 00:18:11,100
Purple.

315
00:18:11,700 --> 00:18:12,700
Take two.

316
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:14,800
l like purple.

317
00:18:15,300 --> 00:18:17,300
l can see that.

318
00:18:22,200 --> 00:18:23,700
l like red too.

319
00:18:25,100 --> 00:18:26,800
Dr. Wheeler.

320
00:18:38,400 --> 00:18:41,800
Excuse me, l have to go
to intensive care now.

321
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:43,800
A nurse should be right in.

322
00:18:45,500 --> 00:18:47,300
Surgical lCU.

323
00:18:55,400 --> 00:18:56,900
What's her status?

324
00:18:57,200 --> 00:18:58,200
Greenly?

325
00:18:58,400 --> 00:19:00,400
Complete squash rot.

326
00:19:00,600 --> 00:19:02,200
She's a total Gomer.

327
00:19:03,300 --> 00:19:04,600
lt's brain death.

328
00:19:17,400 --> 00:19:21,400
That patient was transferred
to the Jefferson lnstitute yesterday.

329
00:19:57,600 --> 00:19:59,600
How can this happen?

330
00:20:00,500 --> 00:20:01,800
All this....

331
00:20:10,100 --> 00:20:12,000
Did you do an EEG?

332
00:20:12,700 --> 00:20:13,600
Flat.

333
00:20:14,400 --> 00:20:16,100
Completely flat?

334
00:20:16,500 --> 00:20:18,200
Completely flat.

335
00:20:19,200 --> 00:20:20,700
Did you repeat it?

336
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:22,400
No, not yet.

337
00:20:23,900 --> 00:20:25,900
What happened during the D and C?

338
00:20:26,200 --> 00:20:27,000
Nothing.

339
00:20:27,200 --> 00:20:30,100
lt's an unremarkable case,
according to the notes.

340
00:20:30,500 --> 00:20:32,500
Transient PVCs late in the operation.

341
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:34,400
Nothing else.

342
00:20:34,800 --> 00:20:35,900
She never woke up?

343
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:41,700
l want to look at her chart.

344
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:59,200
lf it were my friend,
l don't know if l'd be that cool.

345
00:21:03,200 --> 00:21:04,900
The potassium was what?

346
00:21:05,300 --> 00:21:07,300
One-eight? Are you sure?

347
00:21:07,500 --> 00:21:09,300
lt must be a mistake.

348
00:21:11,200 --> 00:21:12,600
Honey, l'm sorry.

349
00:21:12,800 --> 00:21:14,900
l know you two were really close.

350
00:21:17,800 --> 00:21:18,900
Susan?

351
00:21:25,500 --> 00:21:28,400
There doesn't seem to be
anything unusual in the chart.

352
00:21:28,600 --> 00:21:32,000
Normal 28-year-old patient
in good health for a D and C...

353
00:21:32,300 --> 00:21:35,900
...underwent telothane anesthesia,
comes out in irreversible coma.

354
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:40,000
lt's well-documented
that telothane causes liver damage...

355
00:21:40,300 --> 00:21:43,700
...and severe side effects in
a small percentage of surgical cases.

356
00:21:43,900 --> 00:21:47,800
-That's just the risk of anesthesia.
-l know you're upset.

357
00:21:48,500 --> 00:21:50,100
l'm not upset.

358
00:21:51,200 --> 00:21:55,100
You think because l'm a woman,
l'm going to be upset. l'm fine.

359
00:21:56,000 --> 00:21:59,500
l want to understand the variables
as they apply to this patient.

360
00:21:59,700 --> 00:22:01,500
l'm sure you agree that's indicated.

361
00:22:01,700 --> 00:22:02,600
''This patient''?

362
00:22:02,800 --> 00:22:05,600
Here we have an ordinary,
uninteresting case...

363
00:22:05,800 --> 00:22:10,400
...of surgical reaction to telothane
anesthesia in a healthy patient.

364
00:22:10,600 --> 00:22:13,500
As far as l can tell,
there are no unusual aspects...

365
00:22:13,700 --> 00:22:16,800
...except that the patient
was tissue-typed.

366
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:18,200
Tissue-typed for D and C?

367
00:22:19,600 --> 00:22:21,400
There's got to be some mistake.

368
00:22:21,600 --> 00:22:25,400
Here it is. No name on the slip
and no billing number.

369
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:30,700
That's not the first time the lab
ran a test on the wrong patient.

370
00:22:34,700 --> 00:22:38,000
Let's go home.
l think you're tired.

371
00:22:38,800 --> 00:22:42,000
l think l'd better check
the tissue-typing lab.

372
00:22:43,600 --> 00:22:44,400
Why?

373
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:51,400
Nancy's problem was not caused
by wrong lab tests.

374
00:22:53,500 --> 00:22:54,600
l know.

375
00:22:54,800 --> 00:22:56,900
Honey, you're grabbing at straws.

376
00:22:58,000 --> 00:22:59,600
Let's go have some dinner.

377
00:22:59,800 --> 00:23:01,800
-l'm not hungry.
-We'll check the lab later.

378
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:05,000
Stop acting as if
there's something wrong with me...

379
00:23:05,200 --> 00:23:08,100
...or the way l'm thinking!
l'm checking the lab now.

380
00:23:08,300 --> 00:23:09,100
They're closed.

381
00:23:09,300 --> 00:23:11,000
l won't just stand here!

382
00:23:11,400 --> 00:23:13,600
Susan, the lab is closed.

383
00:23:13,800 --> 00:23:15,800
lt closed at six 6:00.

384
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:20,000
ls she all right?

385
00:23:21,500 --> 00:23:24,100
Yeah, she just....

386
00:23:25,100 --> 00:23:26,900
She likes to do things
her own way.

387
00:23:37,200 --> 00:23:38,100
Who's that?

388
00:23:39,100 --> 00:23:40,000
Dr. Wheeler.

389
00:23:40,200 --> 00:23:41,800
We're closed.

390
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:45,000
We don't do any determinations
after six, doctor.

391
00:23:45,200 --> 00:23:47,600
l want to look at
your requisition book.

392
00:23:48,100 --> 00:23:51,500
What does it mean when there's
no name and number on the slip?

393
00:23:51,900 --> 00:23:53,200
There's....

394
00:23:53,800 --> 00:23:56,800
There's always
a name or a number, doctor.

395
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:00,000
For example, Nancy Greenly.
You did tissue-typing...

396
00:24:00,200 --> 00:24:02,500
...but there's no physician name
and billing number.

397
00:24:02,700 --> 00:24:04,100
Let me see.

398
00:24:07,800 --> 00:24:10,500
Yes, you see, it's been
printed out by computer.

399
00:24:10,900 --> 00:24:12,500
That's hospital policy.

400
00:24:12,700 --> 00:24:16,700
A certain number of these tests
are randomly ordered by computer...

401
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:18,200
...as a quality check.

402
00:24:18,400 --> 00:24:20,400
We do the tests here,
they're sent out...

403
00:24:20,600 --> 00:24:22,500
...and done again by an outside lab.

404
00:24:22,700 --> 00:24:25,000
The computer ordered
this test on Greenly?

405
00:24:25,900 --> 00:24:28,000
Yeah, central computer.

406
00:24:28,500 --> 00:24:30,200
Why don't you just show me?

407
00:24:30,400 --> 00:24:31,700
-l can't.
-Why not?

408
00:24:32,100 --> 00:24:33,400
l'm not supposed to.

409
00:24:33,600 --> 00:24:35,100
lt's really important.

410
00:24:36,800 --> 00:24:39,200
Anyway, that information
isn't coded.

411
00:24:39,400 --> 00:24:41,400
lf it isn't coded,
l can't pull it out.

412
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:43,400
l mean, who would want it?

413
00:24:43,600 --> 00:24:46,900
Well, let's say l wanted a list
of all the patients...

414
00:24:47,100 --> 00:24:49,000
...who had tissue-typing
in the last month.

415
00:24:49,200 --> 00:24:50,500
Same thing. Not coded.

416
00:24:50,700 --> 00:24:53,200
What do you do?
What good is all this equipment?

417
00:24:53,500 --> 00:24:54,900
l thought you recorded information.

418
00:24:55,200 --> 00:24:59,500
We do, but the truth is, we install
these computers to bill patients.

419
00:24:59,800 --> 00:25:02,600
We code patient name and number,
medical or surgical...

420
00:25:02,800 --> 00:25:06,300
...admission diagnosis,
therapy and discharge diagnosis.

421
00:25:06,500 --> 00:25:08,300
Okay, wait a minute.

422
00:25:08,500 --> 00:25:11,800
Can you give me a list
of all surgical patients...

423
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:14,200
...with discharge diagnoses of coma?

424
00:25:29,100 --> 00:25:31,000
Okay, we have...

425
00:25:31,300 --> 00:25:34,000
...one general category
under ''coma'' ...

426
00:25:34,400 --> 00:25:37,600
...and nine subcategories
under ''brain syndromes.''

427
00:25:37,800 --> 00:25:38,800
Good.

428
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:41,900
l want a list
of all surgical patients...

429
00:25:42,100 --> 00:25:45,100
...with general category
of coma in the past year.

430
00:25:47,300 --> 00:25:48,400
You're sure you want it?

431
00:25:59,500 --> 00:26:01,000
l had no idea.

432
00:26:01,200 --> 00:26:02,900
lt's a big hospital.

433
00:26:03,700 --> 00:26:05,500
Are you married or what?

434
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:09,400
Thank you.

435
00:26:31,400 --> 00:26:34,300
Surgical lCU. That's right.

436
00:27:04,800 --> 00:27:06,300
Where'd you get this?

437
00:27:08,300 --> 00:27:11,700
lt's against the law.
lt's illegal to tap a data bank.

438
00:27:11,900 --> 00:27:13,200
l don't see why.
l'm a doctor.

439
00:27:13,400 --> 00:27:16,000
-l've got research--
-That's not the point!

440
00:27:16,200 --> 00:27:19,600
Every officer got the lecture.
No access without authorization.

441
00:27:19,800 --> 00:27:21,600
-They can throw you out.
-Never mind that.

442
00:27:21,800 --> 00:27:22,900
''Never mind''?

443
00:27:24,700 --> 00:27:26,000
Look at this.

444
00:27:26,400 --> 00:27:28,000
Two hundred and forty names.

445
00:27:28,200 --> 00:27:31,500
Ten are young people
admitted for minor procedures.

446
00:27:31,700 --> 00:27:34,400
Breast biopsy, appendectomy.

447
00:27:34,600 --> 00:27:37,600
They all come out in a coma.
Aren't you surprised?

448
00:27:38,200 --> 00:27:42,100
The risk of surgical anesthesia
is six per 1 00,000.

449
00:27:42,300 --> 00:27:45,900
ln a hospital this size, 1 0 patients
in a year is not surprising.

450
00:27:46,600 --> 00:27:48,000
So what are you doing?

451
00:27:48,200 --> 00:27:51,600
You missed your rounds.
You didn't scrub in at the gastrectomy.

452
00:27:51,800 --> 00:27:53,100
l had to do something.

453
00:27:53,300 --> 00:27:54,700
Why don't you do your job?

454
00:27:58,900 --> 00:28:01,300
Mr. Murphy is a 35-year-old
in good health...

455
00:28:01,500 --> 00:28:04,800
...admitted for a meniscectomy.
He's scheduled for this morning.

456
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:07,200
Promises, promises.
They keep telling me...

457
00:28:07,400 --> 00:28:09,100
...there's a delay, another half-hour.

458
00:28:09,300 --> 00:28:11,600
Well, the suspense
is really killing me.

459
00:28:11,800 --> 00:28:13,800
l thought you doctors
liked to operate.

460
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:16,500
-We'll get to you.
-l'd hate to be left out.

461
00:28:16,700 --> 00:28:18,100
How did you get your injury?

462
00:28:18,600 --> 00:28:19,800
Playing touch football.

463
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:22,500
You know, with the guys,
horsing around.

464
00:28:23,800 --> 00:28:25,900
<i>Dr. Wheeler, see Dr. Harris.</i>

465
00:28:26,100 --> 00:28:27,800
<i>See Dr. Harris in his office.</i>

466
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:30,200
The chief of surgery himself.

467
00:28:30,600 --> 00:28:32,700
Playing touch football, huh?

468
00:28:32,900 --> 00:28:36,900
Yeah. So l come in,
and all that happens--

469
00:28:40,600 --> 00:28:42,200
Thanks very much, Herb.

470
00:28:42,400 --> 00:28:44,200
We'll get together on it later.

471
00:28:45,600 --> 00:28:46,600
Would you come in?

472
00:28:50,700 --> 00:28:52,000
Excuse me.

473
00:29:04,100 --> 00:29:05,800
Sit down, Sue.

474
00:29:13,900 --> 00:29:15,900
<i>It's Senator Brooke's office.</i>

475
00:29:16,100 --> 00:29:18,800
<i>He wonders if you can</i>
<i>change the meeting to four.</i>

476
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:21,000
Yes, four is fine.
Notify Henry.

477
00:29:21,200 --> 00:29:22,400
<i>Yes, sir.</i>

478
00:29:31,100 --> 00:29:35,500
l like to think that Boston Memorial
is the best hospital in the city...

479
00:29:35,700 --> 00:29:37,500
...perhaps in the country.

480
00:29:38,100 --> 00:29:39,900
l'm committed to it...

481
00:29:40,300 --> 00:29:43,400
...to the house staff we have here,
and to you.

482
00:29:43,600 --> 00:29:45,300
l think you know that.

483
00:29:45,700 --> 00:29:48,500
But we have certain constraints
imposed on us.

484
00:29:49,100 --> 00:29:53,800
One is the state law concerning
privacy in computer data access.

485
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:56,900
An unauthorized entry was made
last night.

486
00:29:57,200 --> 00:29:59,800
We put the young man on probation.

487
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:06,100
But he told us he made
the illegal entry on your behalf.

488
00:30:06,300 --> 00:30:07,200
That's true.

489
00:30:07,400 --> 00:30:11,300
All the discharge diagnoses
of coma over a 1 2-month period?

490
00:30:11,500 --> 00:30:15,100
-l wanted it because l had an idea--
-Well, forgive me.

491
00:30:15,400 --> 00:30:19,000
But it isn't a question
of why you wanted it...

492
00:30:19,200 --> 00:30:21,000
...it's how you got it.

493
00:30:21,800 --> 00:30:25,300
l understand you have personal reasons
for being under stress...

494
00:30:25,500 --> 00:30:28,000
...for not acting as carefully
as you might.

495
00:30:28,700 --> 00:30:32,600
And l'm sympathetic to the way
you must feel about...

496
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:35,000
...the Greely case.

497
00:30:35,200 --> 00:30:36,900
Greenly. Nancy Greenly.

498
00:30:37,100 --> 00:30:40,100
Greenly. Yes, Nancy Greenly case.

499
00:30:43,500 --> 00:30:46,600
l certainly don't want to lose
a good surgical resident.

500
00:30:52,800 --> 00:30:55,300
l think we can handle this, Sue.

501
00:30:55,500 --> 00:30:58,400
